18. illud de Flavio et fastis: in the de li'e Pub. Atticus thought (cf. 8) that Cicero meant to put Cn. Flavius, who published the cal- endar for the benefit of the people (cf. Livy, 9. 46. 5; Cic. pro Mur. 25), before the time of the decem- virs. — tu belle ἠπόρησας, you made a good peina—ut multa (errata) apud Graecos: Cicero wishes to show that his country- men are no more inaccurate with reference to their history than the Greeks are in their history. Cicero prided himself also upon his knowl- edge of nice points in Greek his-

tory and literature, which the dis- cussion gives him an opportunity to air. — Εὔπολιν, τὸν τῆς ἀρχαίας (κωμῳδίας); Eupolis, of the fifth century B.C.‚ was a writer of the old comedy.
